I went to Ellie for my eyebrows throughout my time as a Berkeley student, and she is amazing! She is extremely meticulous and always left my eyebrows perfectly shaped and just the right thickness. She plucks instead of threading or waxing, so there is minimal pain and your skin won't be irritated afterward. Ellie is also very warm and friendly, and her price is reasonable ($15). <user>111652245851974044196</user><date>1542012526558<//date><text>If this were years ago when there was far less competition in the boba world, this place would probably get 4-5 stars easy but since the 626 (and beyond!) has been inundated with a tea shop on every other corner, the bar has been raised and places like Tea Station need to change to keep up.

Service and atmosphere are okay, nothing great. Drinks are- again- okay, not great. They lose a star for the fact that they do use syrups and creamers. I am not a fan of cheap ingredients and additives. I like that they do have a full kitchen and a solid food menu, which a lot of boba places lack.

The last time I was there, I simply ordered their Spicy Wontons. Twenty minutes pass by and nothing... I got the sneaky suspicion that the guy who took my order never actually put it in, so I flagged someone down and sure enough, I was right.

When it finally came out, it was hot and delicious, even though I wouldn't have minded it a tad bit spicier. They apologized when handing me the dish and when the check came for our table, I wasn't charged for my order. That was a proper customer service move on their part and I was pleasantly surprised as service can be bad enough to warrant a one-time visit only.

Thank you, Tea Station staff, for an otherwise flawless evening with my girls.</text><gmapID>0x80c2dab70d6dbffd:0xa68ad8e39d3fb9b2<//gmapID><Resp>None<//Resp>< pictures>

<Text>If you want to drink boba, this is one of the places to go! They have all kinds of drinks here that they can prepare for you. In my experience, they are all very flavorful and enjoyable! You can also adjust the sweetness of your drink, in case you prefer to lessen the sugar level.

In addition to drinks, they have a lot of food items you can order from - comfort food Taiwanese style! You know it's good!

This place also allows you and your friends to kick back and enjoy card games, board games, or just great conversations as a group.  Many also come here to study and read.

There's a more formal section for drinking and tasting tea, in case you are a tea connoisseur. True to their name, they have a wide selection of teas of varying quality you can choose from. 102014649309817812905</UserId.>
<name>Glenn Zucman</name><Date>1486828737047</Date><Rate>4</Rate><text>This is a tricky review to write. I did like Tea Station, but it's also right next to Bake Code and Boba Avenue, so it's hard not to compare. To be fair, all 3 places are different. If you go, a quick peek in each will probably make it clear which place is for you.

Boba Ave is where all the cool Asian kids hang out. This might sound bitter, but I really don't mean it that way: if I were cool, or Asian, or young, I'm sure I'd be hanging out at Boba Ave, but since I'm none of the 3... eh... I might still go there, it's pretty cool, but IDK why I would when Bake Code is right next door. The music there is pretty loud. That might make it fun for you. Since I'm neither cool nor young, it was just loud for me. There was a girl across from me working on her laptop and wearing ear plugs!

Bake Code is home base for me. From the 1st moment I walked in the place I've just been in love with it. Over time I've liked it in different ways. At first it was more of a bakery where I bought a bunch of items to go. Lately it's more of a coffee-tea place where I get one item and some hot milk tea and hang out and work on the laptop. I'm sure Bake Code isn't as cool as Boba Avenue, but for me it's so much friendlier and warmer than Boba Ave or Tea Station. Bake Code definitely has the friendliest employees and their baked items are to die for.

So Tea Station is really fine, but with cool Boba Av and warm Bake Code right next door, I probably won't go to Tea Station again. Not that I wouldn't, just that the other places seem more likely. Interestingly, while the cool Asian kids like to hang out at Boba Ave, Tea Station seems to be the place where the old Asian men like to hang out and play cards. I don't mean to pigeon-hole Tea Station as an older place, I think there might have been young people there too.

Tea Station good, but Bake Code fantastic! And Bake Code is easily half the price of Tea Station, or less. And then you've also got Boba Avenue. Nice to have so many options in one little spot. Haha, with more places across the street! :P<//text>< Pictures>
None<//Pictures>
< Resp>

<Date>1623471079943</Date><Rate>1<//Rate>< text>
Do not take your car here. They do not care about you or your car. I took my car here to get a catalytic converter replaced. They put the wrong one (how? I don‚Äôt know) on and my car did not pass the smog. Instead of handling it with professionalism and remorse I got a handful of attitude and a sense of we‚Äôre doing you a favor contacting the muffler shop. Instead of a real solution, they suggested that I take my car to get the converter certified - basically me cleaning up their mess. In all of this, there was no we‚Äôre sorry this happened. The best they could say was ‚Äúit looks like there might have been a mistake.‚Äù  No. There WAS a mistake. David at the shop, confined to blame the muffler shop which I understand that was where the error happened but I brought my car to G&C so regardless of where the error takes place it should be G&C‚Äôs responsibility to make it right with the customer. Now they are saying they can't get to my car till after the holidays in december. So I have to wait because they dropped the ball essentially. 115047723612248516025</UserId.>

<Review>My review isn't about their donuts or pastries but rather about the way they go about resolving customer disputes.

I stopped here earlier today to cash in a winning lottery ticket.  Attached on top of the ticket was a verification slip, which was stapled by an official at the lottery field office about two miles away.

I was helped by an Asian woman,Susan (?), who appeared confused and initially declined to cash the ticket. She wasn't mean but she didn't exactly make me feel welcome. When she hesitated, I politely asked for the ticket back and said I would go the liquor store a few doors down.

Instead of returning the ticket, she finally read the verification slip out loud: "Retailer pay prize and give exchange ticket to customer....keep original ticket..."

I explained to her that I'd just gotten the ticket verified at the lottery field office and that she was a lottery "retailer".  And as a retailer she should be able to cash the ticket unless the store didn't have the money.

After confirming the ticket amount in the lottery terminal, Susan agreed to give me the cash. Instead I told her that I would be "re-investing" all of the money in additional tickets. Once she tallied all my ticket purchases, she said that I owed her $65 dollars. "What?" While I didn't dispute that fact that I owed her, I disputed that it was $65. What followed next was several minutes of back and forth exchanges, with her insisting that she was right.

Feeling frustrated and that arguing in front of waiting customers wasn't going to help, I asked for the tickets and receipt and left. I wanted to beat traffic but I know now that leaving the store without insisting on a itemized calculation was a BIG mistake.

Before getting home (near LAX), I used my phone calculator to check the receipt. I even took the tickets and receipt to a neighborhood  lottery retailer and explained my situation. He agreed with my calculations: that I owed Homestyle $37, not 65.

He said that the $28 difference was likely caused because Susan didn't clear the lottery terminal before adding my ticket purchases.  The receipt showed I owed $65 because there was $28 balance from a previous purchase.

I don't know if that's true but calling the store an hour after I left proved fruitless. At first, Susan claimed she didn't remember me or our transaction.  Once she did remember, she basically said she couldn't help me because I left the store before resolving the matter.  She was never rude but made it clear that she wasn't about reconcile the matter over the phone. I told I could return to the store any day but today. She finally ended the call by taking my number and agreeing to have the store manager contact me. He never  did. And I won't chase down $28.

Their donuts might be good but I'll never know since I won't be back.  My strong advice to anyone patronizing this place would be to always count your change, always get a receipt, and never leave the store  before reconciling any disputes.</Review>< Name>
Voxwest1<//Name>
< time>

<Time>1536465811900< /Time><Review>Fish was fresh and food was good - everything else was sub-par and kinda ruined the experience.

Pricing was on-par with most decent sushi places ( $13-15 per fancy roll)

Pros:
- food was good quality
- they did have gluten-free options and tamari sauce (gluten free soy sauce)
- hot green tea was not overly smoky
- had a full beer and wine list (not just sake and Japanese beers), which is a nice upgrade
- on-site free parking (it's in a strip mall)

Cons:
- atmosphere sucked - too loud to hear your date (and nearly everyone was there on a date) - we ended up yelljng at each other and mishearing each other all night.
- not really any "best seats" in the house- it's one fairly small-sized room. I kept getting bumped by wait staff on their way to other tables.
- my food (1 roll) came out at least 15 min. Before my date's sashimi plate ... weird. Made for an awkward dinner<//Review><Pictures>[{'url': ['https://lh5.googleusercontent.com/p/AF1QipM_RkIqCK_09TatK6gs05qB-Givq9bMYQw8CSkG=w150-h150-k-no-p']}]</Pictures></record></dataset><record>

<text>Now this place is something special that i hold near and dear to my heart...I started coming here not long ago but instantly knew that i had come to the right place when i met chefs Peter and Ken. These guys are the absolute business, they know what they are doing 100% and can make sure you have an excellent sushi experience. All of the fish is incredibly fresh and prepared the way it should be....ive never had a bad piece of sushi i didnt like from here, as well, the sushi doesnt need sauce, its made the way it should be. and dont forget about that rice tho!! Omg...a little hint of sweet and salt, and it wont fall apart on you when you pick i up.
The Ramen here is also very good...dont sleep on it.

The crew is very attentive to your needs and are always lurking to see if you need anything, but It does get packed here on the weekends and late nights so don't be surprised when you're getting the same attention your wife or girlfriend gives you at home... don't be shy, give em a holler and they will be right there and take care of your needs.

I could go on for days about this place but its time you be the judge.

10/10 always gonna be a favorite of mine.<//text></record>

<Time>1431034908560<//Time>< Rating>
5<//Rating>
<Text>Finally! A solid sushi spot in the city of Long Beach!

A friend recommended Kihon for dinner and I am so happy he did!
The two of us dined here on a Tuesday and it was fantastic! It was quite busy for a Tuesday night. We sat at the sushi bar and was well taken care of by Chef Peter.

Here's what we had:

Smoked octopus carpaccio
Jumbo scallop with kiwi:
Black cod
Golden eye snapper, sea bream, and amberjack nigiri
tuna sashimi
braised short ribs
soft shell crab

The highlights were the nigiris. The fish were delicate and SO fresh. I love that Chef Peter explained how each piece should be eaten. I'm still thinking of the Golden eye snapper and sea bream! The smoked octopus carpaccio is a must get. I love the presentation and there were just perfect amount of lemon oil and yuzu pepper on each bite. The jumbo scallop with kiwi was amazing! Didn't know kiwi worked well with raw seafood! Another hit was the black cod! The cod is marinated in miso for 36 hours and then grilled to perfection! This hot dish was divine!

I must say that Kihon is THE best sushi restaurant in Long Beach! They've been opened for 10 months and I can tell you they aren't going anywhere.

They're currently opened only for dinner but I hear they plan on opening for lunch sometime in the Summer.

Parking: Plentiful</Text>< Pics>
None<//Pics>

<username>K Clark<//username><gmapID>0x808fb6ce78d8174b:0x7b47aad9ea8c54e0</gmapID>< review>
I needed an emergency tooth extraction when my tooth cracked during a dental procedure. MVOS worked me within an hour for the extraction. The staff and the surgeon were kind and professional. They explained the process clearly. The surgeon gave me 3 option for long term issue of what to do with the hole. They explained pros/cons and costs of each option. I've chosen to go with getting an implant. It wasn't fun having a tooth removed and implant material embedded, but they made it as good as it good be. I'm healing well with no complications or problems.  Hopefully, I don't need this done again, but if I do, I will go back to them.< /review>

<userid>108182054803648783208</userid>< name>
Anish Goyal<//name>
<Time>1597186106387< /Time>< rating>
1< /rating>
< text>
I went to the office assuming, they are in my insurance network. However they quoted me charges which were exorbitantly high and when I enquired, they said they are not in my plan. I came back without getting the procedure done. I came home and checked insurance website, which showed Dr Sohoni is in fact in my plan. I called the office back and they told me, insurance says them otherwise. Well, I called the insurance myself and they also told me, doctor is not in the plan. Then I asked insurance, how am I supposed to know which doctor is in my plan and which one is not. The insurance rep checked further and found that the doctor is in fact in my plan.
The next day morning, I called doctor's office and told them the same thing. I requested them twice if they can call the insurance again but they wouldn't agree. They offered me 2 choices. One, they can get pre-authorization which would take 4-6 weeks. Knowing clearly that I have an urgent extraction needed, not sure why will they even offer this. Second choice was, I agree to pay whatever they ask for (~2.5 times the regular billing) and if insurance pays them as I am saying, they'll reimburse me. I don't understand how can someone ask a patient to pay randomly like this. All I wanted was, if they could call the insurance and confirm about my plan again and tell me appropriate pricing.
I don't understand why does the office staff behave as if they are the "super rich" doctors themselves and couple hundreds of dollars here & there makes them no difference.
In the end, doctor is losing a patient and patient is getting hassled.

====

Following up to the response below from the owner. I clearly requested the billing staff twice if they can call the insurance as I believed insurance would give correct information now.
The exact closing reply from them was : "I am not going to call the insurance the third time, if that's what you are asking".
I was told, I have been given 2 options (either wait 4-6 weeks or pay upfront and get reimbursed later if insurance works).
Sorry, you are not the only doctor in the Bay Area. I guess, your staff thinks, I am not the only patient either.<//text>

None< /Pics>

Our billers make every attempt to help you with insurance benefits and claims related questions. We try to streamline insurance claims for our patients, and usually this is a very efficient process.  Rarely though, it can take some back and forth between the insurance companies.  We would be happy to try to work through this with you and clarify any miscommunications so that you can get the care you deserve!'}< /Response>

<username>Medina A< /username><Time>1600122885613<//Time><Rating>5<//Rating>< Text>
I've been a BMW owner since I got my License which was a very long time ago. Each time I've had some "awkward" or weird level of service at other BMW dealers. I heard raving reviews about Peter Pan BMW and I told myself that I will give it another try at Peter Pan BMW since they have the best reviews. I was beyond impressed by this dealer. I was taken care of from the moment my daughter and I walked in. I was greeted by Jim (nicest and most professional human being ever) He gave my daughter and the best greeting ever. Then he asked me detailed questions on what I was looking for and shared his thoughts with me. Since I had contacted this dealer ahead of time he had already had his homework done. He understood my concerns about staying within budget. I was impressed. Since at other dealers once you walk in you automatically become a target for the sales person next commission and they could care less what my needs are. At Peter Pan BMW it was such an incredible experience to know that they actually value me as a person. Then I was introduced to Javed the salesperson who was absolutely amazing. We went over our concerns in detail and he literally showed me 10 different scenarios to make sure that I am getting the best deal. He didn't try to pull a fast one one me like other BMW dealers always do! While we were going through my options and scenarios other members of the team (wish I could remember their names) introduced themselves  and they offered coloring books and other fun activities. I was so shocked. We even watched one of the salesperson granddaughters video which was so cute and it really touched our hearts. My daughter was so impressed now she wants to go there all the time now. As we were going through each of these details Jim was touching base with us each time to see if we were okay and if we needed anything. I personally saw that they were very busy, but they had made each of us customers feel like loyalty. I was able to select the 2020 BMW 530i Sedan  which is very beautiful and I know it fits my personality.  We also had the pleasure of meeting the Finance manager Shakeeb (Shack) he was just as professional and amazing to work with. He was very personable and easy to understand. I had expressed my concerns of being a single mother and how I needed to stay within my budget. He 100% understood me and shared that he had a beautiful daughter and understood my concerns as a parent. I like that Peter Pan BMW followed the covid guidelines which made me feel a little safer to be shopping for a car. The test drive was amazing and after a few lights I knew I wanted the car.  The car was ready and clean. What I want to highlight is that Jim is incredible. He was kind enough to get on a call with my brother (who works at another dealer) to go over my loan and the different scenarios that made sense for my budget. I was very grateful for this extra step. What I really love about Peter Pan BMW is that they didn't take advantage of me and the level of service was beyond measure. Can't wait till I go back when it's time to get a new car!  Heartfelt thanks for all their support and professionalism.  I also like that they respected me a person specially as woman. Since at other BMW's I would feel very violated or the salesperson would speak to me as I'm 2nd class citizen. Peter Pan BMW thank you for the outstanding level of service!! Also, I had 4 different dealers give me BS offers for my trade in value. Peter Pan BMW gave me the most amazing deal. I was even shocked myself. So beyond grateful!<//Text>

< Text>
TLDR: The sales people can be rude, only allow 5-10 minute test drives.

At first, the sales people at Peter Pan seemed very nice and accommodating. I scheduled an appointment for a test drive the day before, and we only waited a short time (10-15 min) for someone to see us. They were very friendly and gave us the keys and told us to take the car out - no further guidance.

We really enjoyed the test drive, it confirmed We liked the car and helped us learn which features were most important. We arrived back at the dealership about 30 minutes after driving off the lot. As soon as I entered, the salesman yelled from across the lobby that I almost got him fired before taking a call as I awkwardly stood there with the keys, and then continued to tell me that I had taken way too long. Apparently, test drives here should only last 5-10 minutes. I don‚Äôt think that is reasonable amount of time to figure out if you want to purchase a car. We were going to test out some other models, but the salesman kept harping on how we had almost gotten him fired and took way too long (despite being given absolutely no guidance beforehand). We decided it was not a good setting to make a major purchase and promptly left. I would look elsewhere before coming to this dealership.< /Text>

< review>
I was promised a price for a BMW X4 and the next day, after I had gone through the trouble of finding a buyer for my old car and planning an 800 mile drive to Seattle (from California), I was told by the general manager of Peter Pan BMW that they are not going to honor their promised price. They said their sales representative hadn't confirm the price with the manager before promising it to me (as a client, I don't think I need to know that).

In case you are curious, the reason why we didn't close the deal the previous day was that we needed time to arrange for the delivery of the car to Seattle and to make sure that they could do that on the timeline at which we needed the car. The sales agent prepared all the paper work for the deal that we had agreed on and everything was ready for me to sign the next day.

Long story short, I ended up having to pay $2000 higher than their promised price to get the car, which, at that point, I had to do to avoid a full collapse of all my subsequent plans (with the sales of my old car and my trip to Seattle coming up). The general manager literally told me that they don't care what the client (i.e. I) was told the day before. He continued, if I had sigend the documents the night before he would have kept the lower price [read: wouldn't have been ABLE to change it to the higher price] but now he was not going to honor their own word.

That all said, the sales people were very helpful and considerate (I wish I could leave a separate rating for that). I think I got the manager on his bad day, but I expect a general manager of a big (and otherwise reputable) corporate like BMW not to pass the ongoing internal frictions and conflicts on to their clients.

I thought this was the end of the drama with the Peter Pan BMW and was glad that I didn't have to go back there again after I leave the lot ... But I was up for a big surprise!

At the noon of Oct 24th, I sold my old vehicle right outside of this dealership to buy the car from the Peter Pan BMW that I had sigend some of the documents for already (including the price breakdown agreement). As I was signijg the rest of the documents the manager came up and summoned the sales representative who was helping me sign the documents ... A few minutes later I was told that they were not going to sell the car to me because they had realized that I had left this review for them (I had posted the sections above this paragraph on Yelp the prior evening). This was utterly upsetting, but I will try to be professional an just write what I observed as opposed to how I feel.

Reading this whole note again, it is possible that the manager's ego couldn't handle the part that I said "[he] wouldn't have been ABLE to [cancel the sale if I had signed the documents]". So, CAUTION!! If, despite my experience, you decide to do business with this dealership make sure you understand that the managerial team here may have a delicate ego and, evidently, this is how they treat customers that they make unhappy, just to protect their delicate egos.<//review>

<Date>1622315816288</Date>< review>
I had the most amazing car buying experience with Henry Sipor at Peter Pan BMW in San Mateo. When I first walked in, I wasn't even sure if I was going to buy a car from there on that day. But after a brief chat with Henry not only he helped me find the perfect car that fit all my parameters, but also he went above and beyond to help me get the best deal and best overall value I wouldn't find anywhere. Trust me I had been looking and observing the market for weeks prior.

Like most people, I always dreaded to spend my entire day buying a car from a large dealership and deal with a lot of haggling and arm-wrestling with the sales team, managers, etc. However, every aspect my interaction with Henry was on point and centered around my needs, my budget and ideal payment terms. He made sure every single question I raised was taken care of to my full-satisfaction. He absolutely good at what he does. He engaged the right parties to help me and his entire team offered my the best customer service one can possibly expect from a premium auto dealership.

In addition to his professionalism, Henry is such an intelligent and interesting man, not only I enjoyed his effortless handling of my car buying experience in a matter of a couple of hours, but also thoroughly enjoyed to chat with him about his background, knowledge, wisdom and utterly positive outlook at life. It's been several days, since I purchased the car, but I am still on the clouds enjoying my car and positive experience I had with wonderful Henry Sipor. If you are in the market for new or used BMW cars, do yourself a favor and go see Henry. He'll make sure you leave Peter Pan BMW as a happy new owner of another ultimate driving machine! :)</review>
